dated as of June 7, 2016 (the Execution Date ), is entered into by and among Boulder Solar Power, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 1 ), Boulder Solar II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 2 ), and Boulder Solar III, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 3 ; (Phase I, Phase 2 and Phase 3 are sometimes referred to herein individually as a Co-Tenant and, collectively, as the Co-Tenants ), and Boulder Solar Power, LLC, in the capacity of the Manager hereunder. The Co-Tenants and Manager are sometimes referred to herein individually as a Party and, collectively, as the Parties. RECITALS A. The Co-Tenants are each separately developing and each separately intend to construct, own and operate electricity generation, storage and/or transmission projects, including solar energy generation projects, on real property in Clark County, Nevada. B. Phase 1 s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 1 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-1 (as the same may be amended pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, the Phase 1 Project Site ). C. Phase 2 s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 2 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-2 (as the same may be amended pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, the Phase 2 Project Site ). D. Phase 3 s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 3 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-3 (as the same may be amended pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, the Phase 3 Project Site ). E. The Co-Tenants respective project sites described above are sometimes herein referred to individually as a Project Site, and, collectively, as the Project Sites, and the Co-Tenants respective projects described above are sometimes referred to herein individually as a Project , and, collectively, as the Projects . F. Each Co-Tenant holds or shall hold its own individual real property rights (by fee ownership, lease, easement, right of way, or otherwise) to its respective Project Site. G. The Co-Tenants are a party to the Interconnection Agreement for interconnection services with NV Energy. H. The Co-Tenants are also tenants in common with respect to, or are acquiring as tenants in common, certain easement, license and permit rights, all of which are more particularly described on Exhibit B-1 (the Shared Premises Agreements ), to use, or will otherwise own fee or easement interests in, certain real property more particularly described on Exhibit B-2 (as amended and supplemented from time to time, the Shared Premises ). The Co-Tenants will require the use and possession of specified portions of the Shared Premises for the construction, operation, and maintenance of their respective Projects. I. The Co-Tenants use of the Shared Premises shall also include the joint design, procurement, development, construction, installation, ownership, use, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and additions to certain common infrastructure facilities supporting the construction, operation and maintenance of their respective Projects, including a substation, electrical transmission and communication facilities, ISP/communication network equipment and service, fiber infrastructure, access roads, and lay-down and staging areas for construction of such common infrastructure facilities, all as more particularly described in Section 1.1, the Shared Facilities. J. The Co-Tenants wish to set forth herein their respective rights and obligations regarding the joint design, procurement, development, construction, installation, ownership, use, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and additions to the Shared Facilities and the joint use of the Shared Premises. K. The Co-Tenants also wish to contract with Manager for the provision of certain limited services to be performed with respect to the Interconnection Agreement, the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises, and the Manager wishes to accept said engagement, on the terms and conditions contained herein. Each Shared LGIA Co-Tenant (other than the Constructing Co-Tenant) agrees that Phase 1 shall have no obligation to fund the other Shared LGIA Co-Tenants share of the Interconnection Customer Construction Costs. 4.6.2 In addition to the Interconnection Customer Construction Costs, each Shared LGIA Co-Tenant shall be responsible for and shall pay or cause to be paid, or reimburse the Manager (or shall cause the Manager to be reimbursed) in accordance with Section 4.3 for, all payments required to be made by the Interconnection Customer to the Participating TO (as such terms are defined in the Interconnection Agreement) under Section 7 of Appendix A to the Interconnection Agreement pro rata based on the Percentage Interest of each such Shared LGIA Co-Tenants, as and when required under the Interconnection Agreement. If an Additional Interconnection Agreement is executed, then the Co-Tenants party thereto shall be responsible for and shall pay or cause to be paid, or reimburse the Manager (or shall cause the Manager to be reimbursed) in accordance with Section 4.3 for, all payments required to be made by the Interconnection Customer to the Participating TO (as such terms are defined in such Additional Interconnection Agreement) under such Additional Interconnection Agreement pro rata based on the proportion each such Co-Tenant s Percentage Interest bears to the total Percentage Interests of all such Co-Tenants, as and when required under such Additional Interconnection Agreement. 5. USE OF SHARED ASSETS. 5.1 Use by Projects. Subject to the other requirements of this Agreement, including Section 3.6, and the Interconnection Agreement and any Additional Interconnection Agreement, each Co-Tenant shall have the rights to transmit and deliver electricity pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement and any Additional Interconnection Agreement in accordance with such Co-Tenant s Capacity Amount. Subject to the other requirements of this Agreement, including Section 3.6, each Co-Tenant that owns a Segment Interest in a Segment of the Shared Facilities shall have the right to use such Segment based on its Segment Interest in such Segment including the capacity of such Segment used to collect, transmit, aggregate, transform, control, shape or otherwise regulate and/or carry electrical energy, including any electrical transmission lines, transformers, substations, and other electrical components (collectively, Electrical Facilities ). 5.2 Shared Facilities Representatives. On or promptly following the Effective Date, each Co-Tenant shall, by written notice to the other Co-Tenants and Manager, designate an individual (the Shared Facilities Representative ), who will have authority to bind the Co-Tenant in all matters concerning this Agreement (other than to amend this Agreement), to communicate on a day-to-day basis with each other Co-Tenant and Manager and to direct Manager s activities in accordance with this Agreements. Each Co-Tenant may change its Shared Facilities Representative at any time and from time to time by prior written notice to the other Co-Tenants and Manager. 5.3 Liens. Except as provided in Section 17.2, no Co-Tenant will create, permit or suffer to exist by, through or under the Co-Tenant or the Co-Tenant s Representatives, and hereby waives for itself and its Representatives, any Liens on the Shared Assets, or on the Undivided Interests or Project Specific Assets of any other Co-Tenant, including (a) Liens for Taxes, unless such Liens with respect to the Shared Assets only are not yet delinquent or which are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, and (b) Liens in favor of carriers , warehouseman s, mechanics , materialmen s, repairmen s or other like Liens, unless such Liens with respect to the Shared Assets only arise in the ordinary course of business of such Co-Tenant and for amounts that are not yet due or which are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, provided, in the case of any such permitted Lien in clauses (a) and (b) above, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any substantial danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Assets and such Co-Tenant posts any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while such claims are being contested. Each Co-Tenant ( Discharging Co-Tenant ) will take prompt steps to discharge any Lien created, permitted or suffered to exist by, through or under the Co-Tenant or the Co-Tenant s Representatives that is prohibited by this Section 5.3. If a Discharging Co-Tenant fails to discharge promptly any such prohibited Lien, any other Co-Tenant shall have the right to notify the Discharging Co-Tenant in writing and to take any reasonable action to satisfy, defend, settle or otherwise remove such prohibited Lien at the Discharging Co-Tenant s cost and expense. A Co-Tenant s rights to pursue remedies at law or equity for a breach of this Agreement by another Co-Tenant shall not be limited by this Section, and may include seeking and placing judgment liens and exercising on same to the extent otherwise permitted by applicable Law and this Agreement. 6. OBLIGATIONS AND CERTAIN RIGHTS OF THE CO-TENANTS. 6.1 Standards of Performance; Action, Omission or Failure to Perform an Obligation that Results in a Material Adverse Effect on Another Co-Tenant or that Co-Tenant s Project. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, each Co-Tenant will develop, construct, operate and maintain its Project and perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with (a) all applicable Laws, (b) Prudent Industry Practices, (c) the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if a party thereto), and applicable Shared Premises Agreements, (d) all applicable Governmental Approvals, (e) all applicable Land Matters, (f) the Power Purchase Agreement which is applicable to the Project, and (g) the terms of this Agreement, including Section 3.6.1. No Co-Tenant will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if a party thereto), applicable Governmental Approvals, Land Matters, or Power Purchase Agreements, that could reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. 6.2 Taxes. Unless otherwise directed by the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall pay all real and personal property Taxes, general or special, levied against the Shared Assets before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty will become due or be imposed for their non payment, except that the Manager may withhold payment of any Tax if Manager is contesting the payment of such Tax in good faith by appropriate proceedings and such proceeding does not involve any danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of such Shared Asset, including the posting of any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while the payment of such Tax is being contested and notifies all the Co-Tenants thereof in writing at least thirty (30) days before such payment is due or paid. All such Taxes and assessments paid by the Manager shall be treated as Shared Expenses and invoiced to the Co-Tenants in accordance with Section 4.3. Each Co-Tenant shall promptly provide Manager with copies of all Tax assessments and other correspondence from or to Governmental Authorities responsible for real or personal property Taxes that it may receive or provide and shall take such actions and execute such documents as Manager may reasonably request in furtherance of its obligations under this Section 6.2. 6.3 Environmental Compliance. Each Co-Tenant shall, with respect to its Project, (including its Project Specific Assets and the Project Site (except any portion of the Project Site covered below)), be responsible for and shall have exclusive control over all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by (i) any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters, or (ii) any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such Co-Tenant s use, operation or ownership of its Project (including its Project Specific Assets and the Project Site (except any portion of the Project Site covered below)) and shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless each other Co-Tenant and Manager from and against any Liability to the extent arising out of or related to such investigations, studies, clean-up, corrective action or response or remedial action. The Manager shall, with respect to the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Premises (including any portion of the Shared Premises which overlaps with one or more Project Sites), subject to the oversight and direction of the Co-Tenants, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Co-Tenants use, operation or ownership of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Premises, and subject to Section 11, each Co-Tenant with an interest in the subject Shared Premises shall be responsible, in proportion to its relative applicable Segment Interest, for all Liabilities related to such investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action. Manager shall keep all Co-Tenants fully appraised as to the above matters affecting the Shared Premises and shall consult with all of them prior to taking any action involving any Governmental Authority or risk of incurring any Liability, and the Co-Tenants with an interest in the applicable portion of the Shared Premises shall manage and control all investigations and any environmental cleanup, remediation or related activities with respect to such Shared Premises, or direct Manager to do so. 6.4 Interconnection. Except as provided for in the Interconnection Agreement or any Additional Interconnection Agreement, each Co-Tenant shall be solely responsible for securing for its own benefit, and for maintaining, such rights as are necessary to interconnect its Project with the transmission and interconnection system of the Interconnection Provider and to deliver the electrical energy generated by its Project, or such portion of the electrical energy generated by its Project, as is consistent with the terms and conditions of this Agreement. 6.5 Operational Data. All Co-Tenants shall make all operational data regarding the Shared Facilities available to the other Co-Tenants upon request. In addition, to the extent required to comply with Governmental Approvals, Laws or NV Energy s rules or regulations, the Co-Tenants shall coordinate and reasonably cooperate with the Manager on management of and shall share operational data regarding the Shared Facilities with the Manager, with the mutual objective of optimizing the operational and maintenance efficiency of the Shared Facilities. The sharing Co-Tenants make no representation or warranty, express or implied, and will have no Liability with respect to the data so provided, whether for completeness, accuracy or otherwise. The receiving Co-Tenants will maintain the confidentiality of the operational data received in accordance with the requirements of Section 13. 6.6 Voting or Approval Rights. Unless otherwise specifically provided in this Agreement, (a) a vote of all of the Co-Tenants shall be required for any approval to be provided by the Co-Tenants hereunder and (b) each Co-Tenant shall have the right to vote or give its approval on any matter requiring or needing a vote or approval of the Co-Tenants. 6.7 Relationship of the Co-Tenants. The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement will be individual and not joint or collective, and no Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the default of any other Co-Tenant under this Agreement, provided that nothing in this Agreement shall alter or amend the Shared LGIA Co-Tenants joint and several liability under the Interconnection Agreement in accordance with its terms. It is not the intention of the Co-Tenants to create, nor will this Agreement be deemed to create, any partnership, agency, joint venture or trust, or to authorize any Co-Tenant to act as an agent, servant or employee for any other Co-Tenant. Each Co-Tenant will remain solely responsible for the actions of its own employees. 6.8 Regulatory Status. Each Co-Tenant operating a Project represents and warrants that, as of the date that such Project is energized, the Co-Tenant will be an EWG or its Project will be a QF, and each such Co-Tenant covenants to maintain its status as an EWG or its Project s status as a QF for so long as it is a party to this Agreement or has any interest in the Shared Assets that requires it to be an EWG or its Project to be a QF. No Co-Tenant will take any action that could adversely impact any other Co-Tenant s ability to qualify as an EWG or its Project to qualify as a QF. 6.9 No Dedication of Property; No Public Access. Each Co-Tenant agrees that entering into this Agreement, performing its obligations hereunder, or exercising its rights hereunder, either in whole or part, is not intended to be, and shall in no way be construed as or deemed to be a dedication to public or quasi-public use or purpose of any of the Project Specific Assets of the Co-Tenant, the Project Specific Assets of another Co-Tenant, any Shared Assets, or any portion of the foregoing. The Co-Tenants also agree that, unless so ordered by a Governmental Authority, there shall be no, and none of them shall provide, public access to the Shared Assets or any portion of them. The Co-Tenants undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting access to the Shared Assets, including establishing and enforcing procedures and protocol for security, safety, and protection of the Shared Assets. To the extent any Governmental Authority attempts to compel the Co-Tenants to provide public access to or use of the Shared Assets, the Co-Tenants shall cooperate to dispute and resist such compulsion by any and all judicial, administrative, legislative, political and other legal means available, unless all Co-Tenants agree otherwise and no Co-Tenants Project is materially adversely affected thereby. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Co-Tenants shall comply with any applicable Laws and Governmental Approvals. Additionally, to the extent any Co-Tenant Project s Governmental Approvals are expressly conditioned on providing a third party access to cross over the Shared Premises, such rights of access do not adversely impact the development, construction, operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities, any Project, or any part thereof, and provided that no public right of access may be created in any Shared Facilities, all of which are the property of and allocated to the Co-Tenants and their respective Projects, the Co-Tenants shall cooperate in good faith and negotiate a resolution of such request to facilitate such Governmental Approvals. 6.10 Crossing and Co-Location Rights. Each Co-Tenant hereunder shall be permitted to cross and encroach upon the Shared Premises with its Project Specific Assets (including collection, communication and fiber lines, gas and water pipes, utility services, and access roads) solely to the extent necessary to develop, construct, operate and maintain or repair its Project provided that any such crossings, encroachments, or overhang shall be subject to the protections and requirements of Sections 3.4 and 3.6 in all respects. Except as otherwise expressly provided in the Shared Premises Agreements, in the event of a conflict in the location or operation of the Shared Facilities and any Project Specific Assets on the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities shall take priority over the Project Specific Assets, and any Project Specific Assets existing within the Shared Premises shall take priority over any subsequent Additional Shared Facilities or Project Specific Assets requiring the use of the Shared Premises. 6.11 Offtaker Collocation of Monitoring and Control Facilities with Shared Facilities. The Parties acknowledge and agree that their respective Offtakers may require the use of the Shared Premises for the collocation of certain control, metering, and monitoring equipment servicing the Projects. The Parties agree to cooperate in good faith to provide their respective Offtakers with rights to use the Shared Premises to so service the Projects. 6.12 Further Development Covenants. If required or necessary to develop its Project by a Co-Tenant, the developing Co-Tenant may request and each Co-Tenant shall, at the sole cost and expense of the requesting Co-Tenant: 6.12.1 Grant crossing agreements and such assignments, grants or sub-grants of rights under its leases and easements and other real property rights constituting the Project Site as requested for transmission, collection, facilities crossings, and/or access purposes relating to the requesting Co-Tenant s Project provided that (a) such crossing agreement or assignment, grant or sub-grant of rights does not violate and is permitted under the applicable lease, easement or other real property right and does not violate applicable Laws or Governmental Approvals, and (b) such crossing agreement or assignment, grant or subgrant of rights and its use could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. 6.12.2 Use commercially reasonable efforts in assisting the requesting Co-Tenant to obtain and to provide new (or amend existing) crossing agreements, subordination, and/or nondisturbance agreements relating to transmission, collection, facilities crossings and/or access purposes, either themselves and/or from any other interest holders in the applicable Project Site, including any mortgagees and fee owners of such Project Site, provided that such agreements could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. 6.12.3 Use commercially reasonable efforts to assist and to cooperate in good faith with the requesting Co-Tenant to seek additional real property rights for the purposes of transmission, collection, facilities crossings and/or access relating to such Project from the Project Sites fee owners, provided that such additional rights could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. 6.13 Cooperation. Upon reasonable request of a Co-Tenant, each Co-Tenant will cooperate (a) in the financing or refinancing of such requesting Co-Tenant s Project, including the execution of estoppels, consents for the benefit of the Financing Parties and other similar agreements as may be reasonably requested by the requesting Co-Tenant and its Financing Parties, (b) in the making of any filings required by such requesting Co-Tenant for regulatory compliance or obtaining Governmental Approvals (filings requiring a Co-Tenant s cooperation shall be subject to prior review and approval of the cooperating Co-Tenant, not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed), and (c) in providing such estoppels or consents for the benefit of the requesting Co-Tenant s Offtaker and other similar agreements as may be reasonably requested by the requesting Co-Tenant and its Offtaker, all solely at the expense of the requesting Co-Tenant, provided that in no event shall a Co-Tenant be required pursuant to this Section to take any action, execute or provide any agreement or document or make any filing which could reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect on the cooperating Co-Tenant. 6.14 Co-Tenants Responsibilities to Manager. The Co-Tenants shall do all of the following: 6.14.1 with the exception of information and data the Manager is required to record and collect hereunder, provide the Manager with all material information, including, permits, agreements, data and documents for the Shared Assets that is reasonably required for Manager to perform its obligations under this Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, the Interconnection Agreement or any Additional Interconnection Agreement; 6.14.2 examine all material documents submitted by Manager and render any necessary decisions pertaining thereto promptly; 6.14.3 promptly make material decisions required under this Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement or any other agreement that the Manager may be requested to administer hereunder and respond to all reasonable requests from Manager for approval made hereunder; 6.14.4 promptly execute and deliver such evidence of Manager s authority hereunder as may be reasonably required by third parties; and 6.14.5 promptly make all payments and incur all expenditures required in connection with the Shared Assets in accordance with this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreement and the Shared Facilities O&M Budget. 6.15 Admission of New Co-Tenants. A Person shall not be admitted as a Co-Tenant under this Agreement (a New Co-Tenant ) without the prior written consent of all of the Co-Tenants, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. It shall be a condition precedent to the admission of a New Co-Tenant that: (i) the New Co-Tenant agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in this Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; and (ii) the Co-Tenants have agreed on, and amended this Agreement to reflect, any changes to the Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages of the Co-Tenants and the New Co-Tenant. 6.16 Reserved Uses for Future Development and Transfers. 6.16.1 If Phase 3 wishes to Transfer all or any portion of its Undivided Interest (including any Segment Interest) to any Co-Tenant or to such transferring Co-Tenant s Affiliate or any third party that is developing an energy generation, storage or transmission project that will require use of all or some portion of the First Circuit and other Shared Assets (each such Person, a Permitted Transferee ), then Phase 3 shall provide no less than thirty (30) days prior written notice thereof to the other Co-Tenants and the Manager, such notice to include the portion of Undivided Interest (including Segment Interests), Percentage Interest, Capacity Percentage and Capacity Amount being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee. Notwithstanding the terms of Section 6.15 or any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, such Permitted Transferee shall be admitted as a New Co-Tenant hereunder (if it is not already a Co-Tenant) effective upon the transferring Co-Tenant Transferring a portion of its Undivided Interest to the Permitted Transferee, provided that it shall be a condition precedent to such Transfer that: (i) the transferring Co-Tenant and the Permitted Transferee obtain any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law in connection with the Transfer, copies of which shall be provided to the other Co-Tenants; (ii) the Transfer does not violate applicable Laws; (iii) the Transfer is not prohibited by and does not otherwise violate the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if the transferring Co-Tenant or Permitted Transferee is party thereto), the Shared Premises Agreements and the Land Matters; (iv) the Permitted Transferee agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in this Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; (v) the Permitted Transferee is party to the Interconnection Agreement or an Additional Interconnection Agreement and has rights to deliver pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement or the Additional Interconnection Agreement up to the Capacity Amount being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee; and (vi) the Transfer could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Upon receipt of notice of a proposed transfer to a Permitted Transferee pursuant to this Section 6.16.1, Manager shall determine the adjusted Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages of the Co-Tenants consistent with the portion of Undivided Interest (including Segment Interests), Percentage Interest, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee, and shall provide notice of such determination to all of the Co-Tenants. Absent a calculation error, Manager s determination of such adjusted Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages shall be binding upon the Co-Tenants and shall be incorporated into an amendment to this Agreement which shall be executed by all of the Parties hereto. 6.16.2 If Phase 3 wishes to Transfer any portion of its Segment Interest with respect to the Last Poles (but no other Segment Interests in the Shared Facilities) to any Co-Tenant or to such transferring Co-Tenant s Affiliate or to any third party, in each case, that is developing an energy generation, storage or transmission project that will require use of the Last Poles and will concurrently acquire rights to use the Second Circuit pursuant to the Second Circuit Agreement (each such Person, a Last Poles Permitted Transferee ), then the transferring Co-Tenant shall provide no less than thirty (30) days prior written notice thereof to the other Co-Tenants and the Manager, such notice to include the portion of Segment Interest in the Last Poles being Transferred to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee. Notwithstanding the terms of Section 6.15 or any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, such Last Poles Permitted Transferee shall be admitted as a New Co-Tenant hereunder (if it is not already a Co-Tenant) effective upon the transferring Co-Tenant Transferring a portion of its Segment Interest with respect to the Last Poles to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee, provided that it shall be a condition precedent to such Transfer that: (i) the transferring Co-Tenant and the Last Poles Permitted Transferee obtain any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law in connection with the Transfer, copies of which shall be provided to the other Co-Tenants; (ii) the Transfer does not violate applicable Laws; (iii) the Transfer is not prohibited by and does not otherwise violate the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if the transferring Co-Tenant or Last Poles Permitted Transferee is party thereto), the Shared Premises Agreements and the Land Matters; (iv) the Last Poles Permitted Transferee agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in this Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; (v) the Last Poles Permitted Transferee will concurrently acquire rights to use the Second Circuit pursuant to the Second Circuit Agreement; and (vi) the Transfer could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Upon receipt of notice of a proposed transfer to a Last Poles Permitted Transferee pursuant to this Section 6.16.2, Manager shall determine the adjusted Segment Interests of the Last Poles consistent with the portion of Segment Interest in the Last Poles being Transferred to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee, and shall provide notice of such determination to all of the Co-Tenants. Absent a calculation error, Manager s determination of such adjusted Segment Interests in the Last Poles shall be binding upon the Co-Tenants and shall be incorporated into an amendment to this Agreement which shall be executed by all of the Parties hereto. Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary contained in this Agreement: (a) a Last Poles Permitted Transferee shall not acquire any Segment Interest other than a Segment Interest in the Last Poles and shall not acquire a Percentage Interest, Capacity Amount or Capacity Percentage; and (b) a Last Pole Permitted Transferee admitted as a New Co-Tenant pursuant to this Section 6.16.2 shall have no voting, consent or approval rights under this Agreement, including pursuant to Section 8.3, but shall retain all of the obligations and liabilities of a Co-Tenant under this Agreement, including pursuant to Section 11 and with respect to costs and expenses to be paid or reimbursed by Co-Tenants pursuant to this Agreement. 6.17 Outage or Disconnection. 6.17.1 To the extent any Co-Tenant s operating Project is disconnected, or its ability to use the Electrical Facilities is adversely impacted or an outage occurs resulting in Lost Revenue, and the disconnection, adverse impact or outage is caused by another Co-Tenant s exercise of rights under Sections 3.4.1, 3.5 or 3.8 or any other provision of this Agreement, the responsible Co-Tenant shall reimburse the Co-Tenant for any Lost Revenue within thirty (30) days of notice and supporting documentation of such Lost Revenue. 6.17.2 In the event of any curtailment of interconnection or transmission services at the direction of NV Energy, in its capacity as Interconnection Provider, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Capacity Percentage. 6.17.3 In the event of any curtailment by an Offtaker pursuant to a Power Purchase Agreement, all such curtailment shall be allocated to the applicable Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities and damages relating to such curtailment. 6.18 Setbacks. The Co-Tenants hereby waive, to the fullest extent permitted by Law, any and all setbacks and setback requirements, whether imposed by applicable Law or by any Person, including any setback requirements described in any zoning ordinance of any Governmental Authority or in any governmental entitlement or Governmental Approvals heretofore or hereafter issued to the Co-Tenants ( Setback ), as they apply to their respective Projects, Project Sites and the Shared Premises, provided that such waiver could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Further, where waiver or elimination of any Setback is not permitted by Law, the Co-Tenants hereby consent to any reduction in such Setback as applied to the Project Sites and Shared Premises, provided that such waiver could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Further, if requested in writing by another Co-Tenant hereunder, each other Co-Tenant, as applicable, shall, at the requesting Co-Tenants cost and expense, (i) execute (and if appropriate cause to be acknowledged) any consent letter to any setback waiver, setback elimination or setback reduction that is consistent with this Section and the terms of this Agreement, and (ii) return the executed consent letter to the requesting Co-Tenant within ten (10) days after the request. To the extent the fee owner of any portion of any Project Site or Shared Premises must waive any Setbacks or consent to any of the foregoing waivers of setbacks, then the Co-Tenants, as applicable, shall reasonably cooperate to obtain such waiver or consent, at the requesting Co-Tenant s cost and expense. The rights granted pursuant to this Section shall be subject to compliance with the other terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (for Co-Tenants party thereto), and the Shared Premises Agreements. 6.19 Permits and Current Zoning Designation. The Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that Governmental Approvals have been obtained, or may be obtained, in contemplation of the Projects having the characteristics described in the Interconnection Agreement (as of the Effective Date) and the commensurate temporary and permanent ground disturbance created thereby, and the Co-Tenants shall not develop any additional facilities without first obtaining new or additional Governmental Approvals, if necessary, as set forth below. The foregoing limitation shall not limit a Co-Tenant from repowering or modifying its respective Project, provided that such Co-Tenant obtains new or additional Governmental Approvals which are not shared with any other Party hereto (or such Party s Affiliates) as required for the repowering or modification, and further provided that such Governmental Approvals, and any of the conditions of approval of any such Governmental Approvals do not adversely impact or affect any other Project. Notwithstanding the foregoing, any Co-Tenant may make such modifications to the Governmental Approvals applicable to the Shared Assets (including amendments, addenda, and supplements to any documents approved pursuant to any Governmental Approvals) as are required to complete the development of its Project and each of the Co-Tenants shall consent to such modifications, provided that such modification could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect, and the Co-Tenants shall all use commercially reasonable efforts in cooperating in any such modifications. 6.20 No Opposition. Each Co-Tenant shall not in any way: (a) challenge, contest, oppose, litigate, comment on (orally or in writing), lobby against or seek to modify, hinder or delay, directly or indirectly, administratively, judicially, publicly or privately, including by referenda or initiative, and will not in any way assist, support, encourage or provide cooperation, direct or indirect, to others who challenge, contest, oppose, litigate, comment on (orally or in writing), or seek to hinder or delay: (i) the processing and issuance of entitlements for the development, use, occupancy, and/or sale of any Co-Tenant s energy related generation, storage, or transmission projects, including any pending or new applications by such Co-Tenant to create new projects in Clark County, Nevada (a Party Project ), or any matter in any way related thereto; (ii) any Governmental Authority s ordinances, Governmental Approvals, approvals or determinations in any way related to the development, construction, use, occupancy, and/or sale of a Party Project or any portion thereof, including any rezoning, conditional use permit, development agreement, tentative or final map, or the conditions applicable thereof; (iii) ordinances, Governmental Approvals, approvals or determinations in any way related to the construction of a Party Project or portion thereof, and/or offsite improvements related to a Party Project; (iv) matters related to the implementation of Party Project s ordinances, Governmental Approvals, approvals, determinations or other entitlements; or (v) any modification, renewal, extension, or amendment of any of the foregoing; or (b) request or support, directly or indirectly, the imposition of any conditions (including any mitigation measures in any environmental impact report or other documents approved pursuant to any Governmental Approvals) by a Governmental Authority in connection with any of the foregoing; provided in each case that the matter in question does not conflict with or violate the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement or the Shared Premises Agreements and the Party Project and the respective Co-Tenant complies with all of the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement and Shared Premises Agreements. 7. APPOINTMENT OF MANAGER. 7.1 Engagement of the Manager. The Co-Tenants hereby engage the Manager as an independent contractor of the Co-Tenants to serve at the discretion and control of the Co-Tenants, to manage, operate, and maintain the Shared Assets, and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets, all as set forth in this Agreement. The Manager accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement. As consideration for the services to be performed by Manager hereunder, beginning on the Effective Date, the Manager shall be paid an annual fee (as adjusted pursuant to Section 7.4.2) equal to the aggregate sum of Thirty-Five Thousand Dollars ($35,000) (the Fixed Fee ). The Fixed Fee shall be payable in equal quarterly installments on the last business day of each March, June, September and December during the term of this Agreement and may be prorated for partial quarters at the beginning and end of the term of this Agreement. If any of the Co-Tenants declare Force Majeure, the Co-Tenants shall nevertheless continue to pay the Manager the Fixed Fee and the reimbursable expenses in accordance with Section 7.4.3. The Fixed Fee shall be allocated among, and paid by, all those Co-Tenants which have connected their Project to the Shared Facilities or commenced the use of any of the Shared Premises, pro rata based on each such Co-Tenant s Capacity Percentage, provided that for purposes of determining each such Co-Tenant s Capacity Percentage, it will take into account the capacity of such Co-Tenant s Project that will be interconnected to the Electrical Facilities upon completion of construction. 7.4.2 Fee Adjustment. In addition to the Fixed Fee, the Manager shall be paid or reimbursed for all work and services provided by or on behalf of Manager pursuant to this Agreement which are (a) in accordance with the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget, (b) in connection with any Emergency or required to comply with applicable Laws or Governmental Approvals applicable to the Shared Assets, including pursuant to Section 8.1.3, (c) listed on Exhibit E-1 and not provided pursuant to the O&M Agreement, or (d) expressly provided for in this Agreement, in each case in accordance with the billable rate schedule set out in Exhibit E-2 (subject to Section 8.2.3) or based on the actual direct third-party costs and expenses incurred by or on behalf of the Manager in connection with providing such work and services. All of the Segment Interests of each Co-Tenant in the Shared Facilities may be referred to from time to time in the Agreement as an Undivided Interest . 2.2.2 Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary contained in the Agreement, if Phase 2 or Phase 3 fails (a) to commence construction of its respective Project within five (5) years after the Execution Date or (b) to commence operations of its respective Project within seven (7) years after the Execution Date (each, a Retiring Co-Tenant ), then effective as of the earlier of paragraph (a) or (b) and receipt of any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law, each Retiring Co-Tenant shall be deemed to have GRANTED, SOLD, TRANSFERRED, ASSIGNED, and CONVEYED, and do hereby GRANT, SELL, TRANSFER, ASSIGN, and CONVEY unto the other Co-Tenant(s) (which are not Retiring Co-Tenants) the Retiring Co Tenant s Segment Interest in each Segment, in proportion to the Segment Interest(s) of the respective transferee Co-Tenant(s), AS IS, WITH ALL FAULTS AND WITHOUT ANY REPRESENTATIONS OR WARRANTIES WHATSOEVER, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, AND SPECIFICALLY EXCLUDING ANY WARRANTY OF TITLE, MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR ANY OTHER WARRANTY ARISING UNDER STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in the Agreement, once Phase 3 (or its successors or permitted assigns) has commenced construction or operations of any portion of its Project, then the retirement provisions of this Section 2.2.2 shall not apply. 2.3 Interconnection Agreement. The Interconnection Agreement shall be shared by the Shared LGIA Co-Tenants as provided for therein. The Co-Tenants acknowledge that the Shared LGIA Co-Tenants are bound to the co-tenancy provisions of the Interconnection Agreement. Phase 3 (or its successors and permitted assigns) may modify the Interconnection Agreement or enter into an additional interconnection agreement to facilitate delivery of power from Phase 3 s Project using the First Circuit (an Additional Interconnection Agreement ) so long as (A) any modification of the Interconnection Agreement or entry into such Additional Interconnection Agreement (i) is for the limited purpose of increasing (or decreasing) the capacity in the First Circuit available for Phase 3 (or its successors or permitted assigns), but does not diminish the capacity in the First Circuit available for the other Co-Tenants in accordance with the Agreement, (ii) any Additional Interconnection Agreement is limited to the First Circuit and the other Shared Facilities, and does not apply to the Second Circuit, (iii) does not restrict, alter or adversely affect the operation, repair, maintenance, or use of the Shared Facilities by any of the other Co-Tenants and (iv) could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect, (B) Phase 3 (or its successors or permitted assigns) pays all costs and expenses associated with entry into such modification of the Interconnection Agreement or Additional Interconnection Agreement, including costs for any additional facilities to be installed by the transmission provider or interconnection customer thereunder, and (C) any Additional Interconnection Agreement appoints Manager as the manager thereunder. Each of the Co-Tenants will agree to execute a modification of the Interconnection Agreement that satisfies the above criteria. In all other events, any modification of the Interconnection Agreement or entry into an Additional Interconnection Agreement for transmission via the First Circuit by any Co-Tenant shall require the approval of all other Co-Tenants, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. Neither Phase 3 nor its successors or permitted assigns may modify an Additional Interconnection Agreement without the prior written approval of all of the other Co-Tenants (which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed) if such modification restricts, alters or adversely affects the operation, repair, maintenance, or use of the Shared Facilities by any of the other Co-Tenants or could reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. 2.4 Shared Premises Agreements and Land Matters. A Co-Tenant s exercise of rights with respect to each Segment Interest shall be subject to the Co-Tenant having rights to use the Shared Premises on which such Segment is located under the applicable Shared Premises Agreements. Each Co-Tenant shall comply with all the terms and conditions of the Shared Premises Agreements to which it is a party and the Land Matters to which it is bound, and each Co-Tenant s exercise of rights with respect to and use of the Shared Premises shall be subject in all respects to the requirements of Section 3.6 of the Agreement and compliance with Prudent Industry Practice and the terms and conditions of all applicable Shared Premises Agreements and Land Matters. No Shared Premises Agreement may be terminated, modified or amended without the consent of all of the Co-Tenants that are party to, or that directly enjoy rights or benefits under, such Shared Premises Agreement, unless such amendment or modification relates only to the interest of the amending Co-Tenant(s) and could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Notwithstanding the immediately preceding sentence, any Co-Tenant may terminate its interest in a Shared Premises Agreement if such termination (a) is permitted by the terms of the Shared Premises Agreement or agreed to by all of the parties to the Shared Premises Agreement and (b) could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect, provided that any such termination shall not cause or be deemed to cause the release of the Co-Tenant from any liabilities or obligations accruing under or with respect to such Shared Premises Agreement prior to such termination. No Initial Land Matter may be terminated, modified or amended without the consent of all of the Co-Tenants that are party to, or that directly enjoy rights or benefits under, or that are directly burdened by or under, such Initial Land Matter, unless such amendment or modification relates only to the interest of the amending Co-Tenants and could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. In addition, no covenants, conditions, restrictions or other encumbrances which are not Initial Land Matters, affecting the applicable real property, and purporting to be binding upon the owner, tenant, licensee, easement holder, or any other user or occupant of that real property shall be binding upon a Co-Tenant as a Supplemental Land Matter unless and until such Co-Tenant has approved such proposed covenant, condition, restriction or encumbrance in writing in advance of the effectiveness thereof, which approval shall not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. For purposes of the Agreement, Initial Land Matters shall mean any and all covenants, conditions, restrictions, and other encumbrances existing as of the Effective Date (other than Laws) and described on Exhibit J to the Agreement, affecting the applicable real property, and binding upon the owner, tenant, licensee, easement holder, or any other user or occupant of that real property. 2.5 Access to Shared Facilities. Each Co-Tenant and its Representatives shall have access to the Shared Facilities for purposes of inspecting the Shared Facilities pursuant to Section 8.11 of the Agreement, all in accordance with the Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, each Co-Tenant shall provide no less than twenty-four (24) hours prior notice to Manager and the other Co-Tenants of its intent to access the Shared Facilities, provided that in the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required, but the Co-Tenant shall provide notice of access to Manager and the other Co-Tenants as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter (no more than twenty four (24) hours after access). A Co-Tenant and/or any Co-Tenant s Representatives shall follow all applicable safety, security and site rules established by the agreement of the Co-Tenants and Manager, and shall comply with the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement and all applicable Shared Premises Agreements, Land Matters, Laws and Governmental Approvals when on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities, except to the extent that following any such rule would violate applicable Laws or Governmental Approvals. 2.6 No Interference, Cooperation and Overburdening. A Co-Tenant s use of the Shared Assets and the development, construction, operation, repair, maintenance, replacement, removal, modification, addition and use of its Project or any parts thereof (including the addition of any storage capacity or the repowering of the Project) or the operations on its Project Site or on the Shared Premises shall be conducted in accordance with the terms and conditions of the Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if the Co-Tenant is party thereto), the Shared Premises Agreements, the Land Matters and applicable Governmental Approvals and Laws and, except for such use in accordance with the foregoing, may not (a) have an adverse effect on the other Co-Tenants, including increasing their liabilities or obligations or diminishing their rights or benefits derived from or their right, title or interest in the Shared Assets or their Projects or the Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement or the Shared Premises Agreements, (b) interfere with the use and enjoyment by and benefits to the Co-Tenants of the Shared Assets or the Projects or the development, construction, interconnection, operation, usage, repair and maintenance of or access to the Shared Assets or the Projects, or (c) create waste or nuisance or otherwise damage or interfere with the Shared Assets or the Projects (including damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of another Co-Tenant s Project or the Shared Facilities), or jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Assets required pursuant to Section 12 of the Agreement or any Governmental Approval required for or applicable to the Shared Assets (any of the effects described in (a)-(c) being referred to herein as a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect ). Subject to the terms and conditions of the Agreement, including Sections 3.4, 3.6.1 and 6.17, each of the Co-Tenants hereby consents to the development and operation of the Projects, and each of the Co-Tenants shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate each of the other Co Tenant s uses of the Shared Assets for the benefit of each other s Projects as contemplated by the Agreement. 2.7 Except as provided in Section 2.3 none of the Shared LGIA Co-Tenants may cause or permit the Interconnection Agreement to be amended without prior written consent of the other Shared LGIA Co-Tenants, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. 2.8 Without limiting Co-Tenants obligations under Sections 3.8, 6.1 or 6.17 of the Agreement, in the event of any reduction of capacity of the Electrical Facilities resulting from an Emergency or an unplanned outage, the Manager shall allocate the remaining capacity of the Electrical Facilities in a non-discriminatory manner among the Co-Tenants in accordance with their Capacity Percentages, provided that if such reduction of capacity is caused by the acts or omissions of a Co-Tenant, then the reduction of capacity shall first be allocated to such Co-Tenant and any further reduction of capacity remaining thereafter shall be allocated by the Manager in a non-discriminatory manner among the remaining Co-Tenants in accordance with their Capacity Percentages. 2.9 No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Project to the Shared Facilities to the extent such interconnection will result in such Co-Tenant having a Project with a nameplate capacity in excess of the following: (a) Phase 1 Project 100 MW; (b) Phase 2 Project 50 MW; and (c) Phase 3 Project all capacity that is not allocated to Phase 1 or Phase 2 (up to 244 MW based on the aggregate rated capacity of the First Circuit of 394 MW). A Co-Tenant s rights to the capacity of the Electrical Facilities (i) when measured in MW as specified in this Section 2.9 (and subject to adjustment pursuant to the last sentence herein) is referred to herein as such Co-Tenant s Capacity Amount and (ii) when measured as a percentage of the aggregate amount of all Co-Tenant s capacity rights as specified in this Section 2.9 (and subject to adjustment pursuant to the last sentence herein) is referred to herein as such Co-Tenant s Capacity Percentage. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Project in excess of its Capacity Amount, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Capacity Amount. The Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that Phase 3 s rights to utilize all capacity of the First Circuit that is not allocated to Phase 1 and Phase 2 shall not constitute an overburdening of such First Circuit or any related Shared Facilities. Subject to compliance with the Interconnection Agreement and any Additional Interconnection Agreement and the requirements of the Agreement, if Phase 3 (or its successors or permitted assigns which are Co-Tenants (other than pursuant to Section 6.16.2 of the Agreement)) interconnects a Capacity Amount that is in excess of 50 MW, then effective as of the date of such interconnection the Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages of the Co-Tenants shall be revised by the Manger. Absent a calculation error, Manager s determination of such adjusted Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages shall be binding upon the Co-Tenants and shall be incorporated into an amendment to the Agreement which shall be executed by all of the Parties hereto. 2.10 Conditions to Installation of Additional Shared Facilities or Connecting Projects to the Shared Facilities. Any Co-Tenant constructing or installing Additional Shared Facilities or constructing, installing or connecting its Project or any Project Specific Assets to the Shared Facilities shall: (a) not interfere with the use or access by the other Co-Tenants of the Shared Facilities, except as may be necessary during the construction or installation of Additional Shared Facilities or the connection of the Project to the Shared Facilities; (b) to the extent commercially reasonable, schedule during an off-peak and/or down-time period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities to construct or install the Additional Shared Facilities or to connect its Project or any Project Specific Assets to the Shared Facilities to minimize the impact on the Projects of the other Co-Tenants or any reduction in the capacity of the Shared Facilities; (c) provide to each of the Co-Tenants and the Manager at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of commencement of such construction or installation activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof; (d) provide at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of any planned outages, and the durations thereof, of the Shared Facilities that would result in a disconnection of another Co-Tenant s Project or a reduction in the capacity of the Shared Facilities; (e) take into consideration, to the extent commercially reasonable, any changes in the construction plans or timing of construction required by another Co-Tenant, provided that the other Co-Tenant does not attempt to interfere with the construction or installation of the proposed Additional Shared Facilities, unless such construction or installation can reasonably be expected to result in an Emergency or violate the terms of the Shared Premises Agreements, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement, the Land Matters, applicable Governmental Approvals or Laws, or this Agreement; (f) be responsible for obtaining and complying with any necessary Governmental Approvals and providing documentary evidence of such Governmental Approvals to the Co-Tenants and Manager; and (g) compensate the other Co-Tenants for any Lost Revenue in accordance with Section 6.17.1 of the Agreement. Any Co-Tenants installing or constructing Additional Shared Facilities that are needed by or would benefit less than all of the Co-Tenants, or constructing, installing or connecting its own Project or Project Specific Assets to the Shared Facilities, shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants from all Liabilities to the extent arising out of or related to such activities, to the extent such Liabilities are not covered by the insurance required by Section 12 of the Agreement. Installation and construction of Additional Shared Facilities to be owned by more than one Co-Tenant shall be constructed and installed jointly by the participating Co-Tenants or by the Manager at the direction of the participating Co-Tenants, and will be at the risk of all the participating Co-Tenants, and each participating Co-Tenant shall have the right to review and approve all design, planning and installation elements in connection with such construction and installation, and will bear any risk of loss thereof in proportion with its Segment Interest in the Additional Shared Facilities, to the extent such loss is not covered by the insurance required by Section 12 of the Agreement. 3. SHARED EXPENSES AND CONSTRUCTION COSTS. The Co-Tenants shall be responsible for and shall pay or shall reimburse the Manager for Shared Expenses relating to the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises and shall be responsible for and shall pay for the costs and expenses, including Construction Costs, to design, engineer, procure, install, construct and permit the Shared Facilities and all other Construction Costs in accordance with the provisions of Section 4 of the Agreement. 4. OBLIGATIONS AND CERTAIN RIGHTS OF THE CO-TENANTS. 4.1 No Dedication of Property; No Public Access. Each Co-Tenant agrees that entering into the Agreement, performing its obligations thereunder, or exercising its rights thereunder, either in whole or part, is not intended to be, and shall in no way be construed as or deemed to be a dedication to public or quasi-public use or purpose of any of the Project Specific Assets of the Co-Tenant, the Project Specific Assets of another Co-Tenant, any Shared Assets, or any portion of the foregoing. The Co-Tenants also agree that, unless so ordered by a Governmental Authority, there shall be no, and none of them shall provide, public access to the Shared Assets or any portion of them. The Co-Tenants undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting access to the Shared Assets, including establishing and enforcing procedures and protocol for security, safety, and protection of the Shared Assets. 4.2 Crossing and Co-Location Rights. Each Co-Tenant hereunder shall be permitted to cross and encroach upon the Shared Premises with its Project Specific Assets (including collection, communication and fiber lines, gas and water pipes, utility services, and access roads) solely to the extent necessary to develop, construct, operate and maintain or repair its Project provided that any such crossings, encroachments, or overhang shall be subject to the protections and requirements of Sections 3.4 and 3.6 of the Agreement in all respects. Except as otherwise expressly provided in the Shared Premises Agreements, in the event of a conflict in the location or operation of the Shared Facilities and any Project Specific Assets on the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities shall take priority over the Project Specific Assets, and any Project Specific Assets existing within the Shared Premises shall take priority over any subsequent Additional Shared Facilities or Project Specific Assets requiring the use of the Shared Premises. 4.3. Relationship of the Co-Tenants. The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the Co-Tenants under the Agreement will be individual and not joint or collective, and no Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the default of any other Co-Tenant under the Agreement, provided that nothing in the Agreement shall alter or amend the Shared LGIA Co-Tenants joint and several liability under the Interconnection Agreement in accordance with its terms. It is not the intention of the Co-Tenants to create, nor will the Agreement be deemed to create, any partnership, agency, joint venture or trust, or to authorize any Co-Tenant to act as an agent, servant or employee for any other Co-Tenant. Each Co-Tenant will remain solely responsible for the actions of its own employees. 4.4 Admission of New Co-Tenants. A Person shall not be admitted as a Co-Tenant under the Agreement (a New Co-Tenant ) without the prior written consent of all of the Co-Tenants, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. It shall be a condition precedent to the admission of a New Co-Tenant that: (i) the New Co-Tenant agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in the Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; and (ii) the Co-Tenants have agreed on, and amended the Agreement to reflect, any changes to the Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages of the Co-Tenants and the New Co-Tenant. 4.5 Reserved Uses for Future Development and Transfers. 4.5.1 If Phase 3 wishes to Transfer all or any portion of its Undivided Interest (including any Segment Interest) to any Co-Tenant or to such transferring Co-Tenant s Affiliate or any third party that is developing an energy generation, storage or transmission project that will require use of all or some portion of the First Circuit and other Shared Assets (each such Person, a Permitted Transferee ), then Phase 3 shall provide no less than thirty (30) days prior written notice thereof to the other Co-Tenants and the Manager, such notice to include the portion of Undivided Interest (including Segment Interests), Percentage Interest, Capacity Percentage and Capacity Amount being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee. Notwithstanding the terms of Section 6.15 or any other provision of the Agreement to the contrary, such Permitted Transferee shall be admitted as a New Co-Tenant hereunder (if it is not already a Co-Tenant) effective upon the transferring Co-Tenant Transferring a portion of its Undivided Interest to the Permitted Transferee, provided that it shall be a condition precedent to such Transfer that: (i) the transferring Co-Tenant and the Permitted Transferee obtain any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law in connection with the Transfer, copies of which shall be provided to the other Co-Tenants; (ii) the Transfer does not violate applicable Laws; (iii) the Transfer is not prohibited by and does not otherwise violate the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if the transferring Co-Tenant or Permitted Transferee is party thereto), the Shared Premises Agreements and the Land Matters; (iv) the Permitted Transferee agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in the Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; (v) the Permitted Transferee is party to the Interconnection Agreement or an Additional Interconnection Agreement and has rights to deliver pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement or the Additional Interconnection Agreement up to the Capacity Amount being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee; and (vi) the Transfer could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Upon receipt of notice of a proposed transfer to a Permitted Transferee pursuant to this Section 4.5.1, Manager shall determine the adjusted Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages of the Co-Tenants consistent with the portion of Undivided Interest (including Segment Interests), Percentage Interest, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages being Transferred to the Permitted Transferee, and shall provide notice of such determination to all of the Co-Tenants. Absent a calculation error, Manager s determination of such adjusted Undivided Interests, Segment Interests, Percentage Interests, Capacity Amounts and Capacity Percentages shall be binding upon the Co-Tenants and shall be incorporated into an amendment to the Agreement which shall be executed by all of the Parties hereto. 4.5.2 If Phase 3 wishes to Transfer any portion of its Segment Interest with respect to the Last Poles (but no other Segment Interests in the Shared Facilities) to any Co-Tenant or to such transferring Co-Tenant s Affiliate or to any third party, in each case, that is developing an energy generation, storage or transmission project that will require use of the Last Poles and will concurrently acquire rights to use the Second Circuit pursuant to the Second Circuit Agreement (each such Person, a Last Poles Permitted Transferee ), then the transferring Co-Tenant shall provide no less than thirty (30) days prior written notice thereof to the other Co-Tenants and the Manager, such notice to include the portion of Segment Interest in the Last Poles being Transferred to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee. Notwithstanding the terms of Section 6.15 or any other provision of the Agreement to the contrary, such Last Poles Permitted Transferee shall be admitted as a New Co-Tenant hereunder (if it is not already a Co-Tenant) effective upon the transferring Co-Tenant Transferring a portion of its Segment Interest with respect to the Last Poles to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee, provided that it shall be a condition precedent to such Transfer that: (i) the transferring Co-Tenant and the Last Poles Permitted Transferee obtain any Governmental Approvals required by applicable Law in connection with the Transfer, copies of which shall be provided to the other Co-Tenants; (ii) the Transfer does not violate applicable Laws; (iii) the Transfer is not prohibited by and does not otherwise violate the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (if the transferring Co-Tenant or Last Poles Permitted Transferee is party thereto), the Shared Premises Agreements and the Land Matters; (iv) the Last Poles Permitted Transferee agrees in writing to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained in the Agreement, including Sections 3.4 and 3.6; (v) the Last Poles Permitted Transferee will concurrently acquire rights to use the Second Circuit pursuant to the Second Circuit Agreement; and (vi) the Transfer could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Upon receipt of notice of a proposed transfer to a Last Poles Permitted Transferee pursuant to this Section 4.5.2, Manager shall determine the adjusted Segment Interests of the Last Poles consistent with the portion of Segment Interest in the Last Poles being Transferred to the Last Poles Permitted Transferee, and shall provide notice of such determination to all of the Co-Tenants. Absent a calculation error, Manager s determination of such adjusted Segment Interests in the Last Poles shall be binding upon the Co-Tenants and shall be incorporated into an amendment to the Agreement which shall be executed by all of the Parties hereto. Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary contained in the Agreement: (a) a Last Poles Permitted Transferee shall not acquire any Segment Interest other than a Segment Interest in the Last Poles and shall not acquire a Percentage Interest, Capacity Amount or Capacity Percentage; and (b) a Last Pole Permitted Transferee admitted as a New Co-Tenant pursuant to this Section 4.5.2 shall have no voting, consent or approval rights under the Agreement, including pursuant to Section 8.3, but shall retain all of the obligations and liabilities of a Co-Tenant under the Agreement, including pursuant to Section 11 and with respect to costs and expenses to be paid or reimbursed by Co-Tenants pursuant to the Agreement. 4.6 Outage or Disconnection. 4.6.1 To the extent any Co-Tenant s operating Project is disconnected, or its ability to use the Electrical Facilities is adversely impacted or an outage occurs resulting in Lost Revenue, and the disconnection, adverse impact or outage is caused by another Co-Tenant s exercise of rights under Sections 3.4.1, 3.5 or 3.8 or any other provision of the Agreement, the responsible Co-Tenant shall reimburse the Co-Tenant for any Lost Revenue within thirty (30) days of notice and supporting documentation of such Lost Revenue. 4.6.2 In the event of any curtailment of interconnection or transmission services at the direction of NV Energy, in its capacity as Interconnection Provider, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Capacity Percentage. 4.6.3 In the event of any curtailment by an Offtaker pursuant to a Power Purchase Agreement, all such curtailment shall be allocated to the applicable Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities and damages relating to such curtailment. 4.7 Setbacks. The Co-Tenants hereby waive, to the fullest extent permitted by Law, any and all setbacks and setback requirements, whether imposed by applicable Law or by any Person, including any setback requirements described in any zoning ordinance of any Governmental Authority or in any governmental entitlement or Governmental Approvals heretofore or hereafter issued to the Co-Tenants ( Setback ), as they apply to their respective Projects, Project Sites and the Shared Premises, provided that such waiver could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Further, where waiver or elimination of any Setback is not permitted by Law, the Co-Tenants hereby consent to any reduction in such Setback as applied to the Project Sites and Shared Premises, provided that such waiver could not reasonably be expected to have a Co-Tenant Adverse Effect. Further, if requested in writing by another Co-Tenant hereunder, each other Co-Tenant, as applicable, shall, at the requesting Co-Tenants cost and expense, (i) execute (and if appropriate cause to be acknowledged) any consent letter to any setback waiver, setback elimination or setback reduction that is consistent with this Section and the terms of the Agreement, and (ii) return the executed consent letter to the requesting Co-Tenant within ten (10) days after the request. To the extent the fee owner of any portion of any Project Site or Shared Premises must waive any Setbacks or consent to any of the foregoing waivers of setbacks, then the Co-Tenants, as applicable, shall reasonably cooperate to obtain such waiver or consent, at the requesting Co-Tenant s cost and expense. The rights granted pursuant to this Section shall be subject to compliance with the other terms and conditions of the Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, any Additional Interconnection Agreement (for Co-Tenants party thereto), and the Shared Premises Agreements. 4.8 Liens. Except as provided in Section 17.2 of the Agreement, no Co-Tenant will create, permit or suffer to exist by, through or under the Co-Tenant or the Co-Tenant s Representatives, and hereby waives for itself and its Representatives, any Liens on the Shared Assets, or on the Undivided Interests or Project Specific Assets of any other Co-Tenant, including (a) Liens for Taxes, unless such Liens with respect to the Shared Assets only are not yet delinquent or which are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, and (b) Liens in favor of carriers , warehouseman s, mechanics , materialmen s, repairmen s or other like Liens, unless such Liens with respect to the Shared Assets only arise in the ordinary course of business of such Co-Tenant and for amounts that are not yet due or which are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, provided, in the case of any such permitted Lien in clauses (a) and (b) above, so long as any such proceeding does not involve any substantial danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Shared Assets and such Co-Tenant posts any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while such claims are being contested. Each Co-Tenant ( Discharging Co-Tenant ) will take prompt steps to discharge any Lien created, permitted or suffered to exist by, through or under the Co-Tenant or the Co-Tenant s Representatives that is prohibited by Section 5.3 of the Agreement. If a Discharging Co-Tenant fails to discharge promptly any such prohibited Lien, any other Co-Tenant shall have the right to notify the Discharging Co-Tenant in writing and to take any reasonable action to satisfy, defend, settle or otherwise remove such prohibited Lien at the Discharging Co-Tenant s cost and expense. A Co-Tenant s rights to pursue remedies at law or equity for a breach of the Agreement by another Co-Tenant shall not be limited by this Section, and may include seeking and placing judgment liens and exercising on same to the extent otherwise permitted by applicable Law and the Agreement. 4.9 Use by Projects. Subject to the other requirements of the Agreement, including Section 3.6 of the Agreement, and the Interconnection Agreement and any Additional Interconnection Agreement, each Co-Tenant shall have the rights to transmit and deliver electricity pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement and any Additional Interconnection Agreement in accordance with such Co-Tenant s Capacity Amount. Subject to the other requirements of the Agreement, including Section 3.6 of the Agreement, each Co-Tenant that owns a Segment Interest in a Segment of the Shared Facilities shall have the right to use such Segment based on its Segment Interest in such Segment including the capacity of such Segment used to collect, transmit, aggregate, transform, control, shape or otherwise regulate and/or carry electrical energy, including any electrical transmission lines, transformers, substations, and other electrical components (collectively, Electrical Facilities ). 5.
